				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: song twisting....what's normal?!?!?!<a name="32303"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 1 04 1:44 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>You can, assuming no missed notes, keep 4 up easily with a macro. With 5 you end up with times where there are songs down.
<br />

<br />
The problem with macros is that a good bard twists different songs as the mob goes through its life and death phases.  If you're macro'd, you certainly can swap out and alter your lineup as the mob's health drops, but you probably don't.
<br />

<br />
Phase 1 - Mob is incoming, slowed, taunted:
<br />

<br />
I twist certain songs (HoS, my dot/slow (cause free damage and a pre-slow is handy), sometimes a snare, and Warsong of Zek. I don't worry about mana song. I'm not really worried in those first 12 seconds about overhaste or amping spell damage. No one is going to be nuking/DoTting in the first little bit of a mob's health while the tank is establishing aggro. Or am I worried about resists? It depends on the mob and the party. 
<br />

<br />
Phase 2 - Most of the fight
<br />
Call of the Muse joins Zek as DoTs begin to land. Usually Marr joins the twist to make sure mana holds up, but not always. If I know my casters can handle it, I keep the mob HoS'd so that nukes won't be resisted. Sometimes I pop in four (muse, zek, marr, hos), but I don't want my haste, ds, or overhaste to fall.
<br />

<br />
Phase 3 - The mob grows weak.
<br />
Does the mob need to be snared? Are the wizards going to med from 20% down, or are they going to burn it down? If so, I need to keep it HoS'd and muse needs to stay up. If not, I may turn to other things, or to the next pull. Do I have lots of melee dps and I need to keep overhaste/atk going strong? Will he gate and I need to interrupt? Is the cleric going to have the mana to heal on the next pull? So many interations, so many possibilities.
<br />

<br />
My point is that I consider myself a very good bard. I twist three songs. I use no macros. The glory of the bard is our flexibility, our skill at assuming almost any role, at making almost everyone better. But for the life of any one mob, those needs change. Change with them. Don't get locked into a twist.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"></span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td height="2"></td>
			</tr><tr>
